rld.org/blog/articles/lisps/why-i-still-reach-for-scheme-instead-of-haskell/index.html\" rel=\"ugc\"\u003ehttps://jointhefreeworld.org/blog/articles/lisps/why-i-still-reach-for-scheme-instead-of-haskell/index.html\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"After reading the original article https://web.archive.org/web/20121204010925/https://slidetocode.com/2012/04/09/why-i-prefer-scheme-to-haskell/\r\n\r\nI realized it really resonated with me and was actually telling my story (partially). So I wrote my own article on this topic. Hope you enjoy:\r\n\r\nhttps://jointhefreeworld.org/blog/articles/lisps/why-i-still-reach-for-scheme-instead-of-haskell/index.html","submitter_user":"jjba23","user_is_author":true,"tags":["haskell","lisp","programming"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tzqafn","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/tzqafn/why_i_still_reach_for_lisp_scheme_instead"},{"short_id":"ijkf8e","created_at":"2026-04-30T03:51:00.000-05:00","title":"March in Servo: keyboard navigation, better debugging, FreeBSD support, and more","url":"https://servo.org/blog/2026/04/30/march-in-servo/","score":12,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"FedericoSchonborn","user_is_author":false,"tags":["browsers"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ijkf8e","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/ijkf8e/march_servo_keyboard_navigation_better"},{"short_id":"heoyfd","created_at":"2026-04-30T04:00:30.000-05:00","title":"Amber-Lang 0.6.0 - New release, check what's new","url":"https://docs.amber-lang.com/getting_started/whats_new","score":5,"flags":0,"comment_count":0,"description":"\u003cp\u003eAs per title finally after more then 6 months we are releasing the new 0.6.0 release!\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIn this release we put a lot of effort on looking on feedbacks after the Fosdem talks and reception we got on socials.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThis release brings multi-shell support (Bash, Zsh, Ksh, and even Bash 3.2), making it easier to deploy scripts across different UNIX environments. Key additions include recursive functions, union types, and public (pub) variables for better modularity.\u003cbr\u003e\nThe language also introduces a built-in testing suite with assert and assert_eq, plus stricter validation for failable functions and variable usage.\u003cbr\u003e\nPerformance gets a boost with native Bash arithmetic for integer operations, reducing dependencies on bc/sed.\u003cbr\u003e\nNew builtins like fetch() for HTTP requests, touch(), rm(), and ls() expand Amber’s capabilities, while the license switch to LGPL makes it more friendly for proprietary projects.\u003cbr\u003e\nBreaking changes include mandatory parentheses for builtins (e.g., echo(\"text\")) and stricter error handling for out-of-bounds array access.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIncluding Debian/RPM packages, improved CI/CD with nightly builds, and better shellcheck integration. The standard library grows with helpers for filesystem, environment, and text manipulation.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWe are still a lot of stuff to do but we are proceeding faster as we are getting more contributors :-D\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"As per title finally after more then 6 months we are releasing the new 0.6.0 release!\r\n\r\nIn this release we put a lot of effort on looking on feedbacks after the Fosdem talks and reception we got on socials.\r\n\r\nThis release brings multi-shell support (Bash, Zsh, Ksh, and even Bash 3.2), making it easier to deploy scripts across different UNIX environments. Key additions include recursive functions, union types, and public (pub) variables for better modularity.  \r\nThe language also introduces a built-in testing suite with assert and assert_eq, plus stricter validation for failable functions and variable usage.  \r\nPerformance gets a boost with native Bash arithmetic for integer operations, reducing dependencies on bc/sed.  \r\nNew builtins like fetch() for HTTP requests, touch(), rm(), and ls() expand Amber’s capabilities, while the license switch to LGPL makes it more friendly for proprietary projects.  \r\nBreaking changes include mandatory parentheses for builtins (e.g., echo(\"text\")) and stricter error handling for out-of-bounds array access.\r\n\r\nIncluding Debian/RPM packages, improved CI/CD with nightly builds, and better shellcheck integration. The standard library grows with helpers for filesystem, environment, and text manipulation.\r\n\r\nWe are still a lot of stuff to do but we are proceeding faster as we are getting more contributors :-D","submitter_user":"Mte90","user_is_author":true,"tags":["linux","programming","unix"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/heoyfd","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/heoyfd/amber_lang_0_6_0_new_release_check_what_s_new"},{"short_id":"8wsxnj","created_at":"2026-04-29T19:41:09.000-05:00","title":"Your Clippy Config Should Be Stricter","url":"https://emschwartz.me/your-clippy-config-should-be-stricter/","score":11,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"emschwartz","user_is_author":true,"tags":["rust","vibecoding"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/8wsxnj","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/8wsxnj/your_clippy_config_should_be_stricter"},{"short_id":"djfjlg","created_at":"2026-04-29T10:16:21.000-05:00","title":"KDE’s 30th anniversary","url":"https://kde.org/anniversaries/30/","score":52,"flags":0,"comment_count":1,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"hugoarnal","user_is_author":false,"tags":["linux","release"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/djfjlg","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/djfjlg/kde_s_30th_anniversary"},{"short_id":"yn7tfr","created_at":"2026-04-28T23:17:13.000-05:00","title":"Bugs Rust Won't Catch","url":"https://corrode.dev/blog/bugs-rust-wont-catch/","score":71,"flags":0,"comment_count":26,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"PuercoPop","user_is_author":false,"tags":["rust"],"short_id_ur